    oneLiner: "The ninth-century rift between Rome and Constantinople under Patriarch Photius, foreshadowing the Great Schism of 1054.",
    body: "The Photian Schism arose in 863 when Pope Nicholas I refused to recognize Photius as the legitimate Patriarch of Constantinople, supporting the deposed Patriarch Ignatius instead. Photius responded by challenging Rome's authority and condemning the Western addition of the Filioque clause to the Nicene Creed. He convened a council in 867 that excommunicated the Pope. Though the schism was formally healed at the Fourth Council of Constantinople (869-870), the underlying tensions over papal primacy, the Filioque, and jurisdiction over newly evangelized Slavic lands persisted and eventually erupted in the definitive break of 1054.",
